Slope reinforcement indicator¶

Life cycle of Machine learning Project¶

  • Understanding the problem statement
  • Data collection
  • Data checks to perform
  • Exploratory data analysis
  • Data Pre-processing
  • Model trainning
  • Choose the best model

1) Problem Statement¶

The slope stability problem is usually solved using a software, which can be finite element software or limit equilibrium software. To design a support system, an engineer have to iterate over different desings proposed by him, this task take a lot of time since just experienced engineers know where to start.

$\bullet$ For this reason a Slope reinforcement indicator is formulated, to standarize and optimize the process of support selection and avoid estimates.

2) Data collection¶

  • The data source is provided in 25 different csv files where every csv file is associated with a combination of initial input variables in Main_config.xlsx file. Every csv file contains information about different soil conditions, soil resistance properties, and the associated resistance factor (Factor of safety).
  • The dataset consist of 25 different geometrical conditions associated with 5000 simulations results each.

2.2) Dataset information¶

  • Cohesion: the cohesion of soils, a resistance parameter from mohr coulomb criterion
  • Phi (φ): friction angle of soils
  • Unit Weight (γ): unit weight of soils
  • Pe (External load): Load present in the crown of the slope
  • Ps (Support Pressure): Load that represents the support system
  • FS s: factor of safety obtained with the Spencer method
  • FS gmp: factor of safety obtained with the GM-P method
  • Slope angle (α): angle of the base of the slope
  • Slope height (H): Height of the slope

We proceed to visualize the effects of different variables with $\phi$.

In [17]:
fig,axs = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(10,5))

df_main_n = df_main[df_main.iloc[:,3] < 3]


names   = ["Phi","Cohesion"]
names_i = [r"$\phi$", r"$c$"]

for i in range(0,2):
    ax = sns.scatterplot(x = df_main_n[names[i]] ,
                        y = df_main_n["FSs"],
                        hue= df_main_n["slope_height"],
                        size= df_main_n["slope_height"],
                        palette="viridis",
                        legend= True,
                        ax = axs[i])

    ax.set(xlabel = names_i[i])
    ax.set(ylabel = r"$FS_{spencer}$")
    ax.legend(title = r"$H$")



fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

It is observable that as the slope height $H$ reduces the $FS$ increases.
